She shows how civic groups and elected officials crafted a series of visions and plans for local food systems that informed the 2011 update to PlaNYC. City of Forests, City of Farms is a valuable tool that allows us to understand and disentangle the political decisions, popular narratives, and physical practices that shape city greening in New York City and elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningxEnvironmental aspectszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEnvironmental policyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aGreen movementzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHuman ecologyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aLand use, UrbanxEnvironmental aspectszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aLand use, UrbanzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSustainable livingzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban agriculturezNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban ecology (Biology)zNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban forestryzNew York (State)zNew York. 4aArchitecture & Preservation. 4aNew York History. 4aUrban Studies.  aPlanNYC, land use planning, urban sustainability, New York City, nature conservation, green infrastructure, community gardening, community engagement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501714795?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714795/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles